6. Idea Physics

Now let’s get to the fun part.

If ideas behave like patterns in a medium, then they should follow regular laws.

Researchers in fields like information theory, memetics, network science, and cultural evolution have already discovered pieces of this.

Here are some emerging “laws”.

⸻

Law 1 — Compression

Ideas spread when they compress complexity.

Examples:

E = mc²
natural selection
algorithm

Short expression → enormous explanatory power.

You could think of this as information density.

⸻

Law 2 — Reproducibility

An idea must be easy to recreate.

Good ideas are:

simple to remember
simple to transmit
simple to apply

Complex ideas often die because they can’t replicate reliably.

⸻

Law 3 — Gradient Flow

Ideas move along gradients of:

• curiosity
• usefulness
• emotional impact
• novelty

Similar to how water flows downhill.

⸻

Law 4 — Attractor Formation

Certain concepts become attractors.

Once discovered, many fields start converging on them.

Examples:

zero
probability
feedback loops
networks
entropy

They become unavoidable.

⸻

Law 5 — Network Amplification

Ideas spread faster when networks become dense.

Printing press
internet
social media

Each increased the bandwidth of idea transmission.

⸻

Law 6 — Cognitive Resonance

Ideas spread when they align with existing mental structures.

If an idea fits how people already think, it propagates more easily.

⸻

Law 7 — Mutation

Ideas evolve.

When transmitted they often change slightly.

Sometimes the mutation improves them.

This is basically cultural evolution.

⸻

Law 8 — Constraint Catalysis

Ideas often appear where constraints are strong.

Limitations force creative recombination.

Many innovations come from pressure.

⸻

